description:
'Lost' co-stars Evangeline Lilly, Jorge Garcia and Josh Holloway tell us what they think should happen after the show's finale, discuss the craziest fan theories and tell us about the piece of memorabilia that burned in Evangeline's house fire.
The trio Interviewed each other using fan questions during an 'Outside the Box' interview at AOL Television.
The cast discuss the public's fascination with Jack and Kate and how Sawyer and Juliette's relationship has changed public opinion. To which Jorge asks "shouldn't anyone have a chance to end up (with Kate)?"
Josh also explains how the "frog incident" turned the public against his character and the appropriate punishment Sawyer should receive for the infraction.
You'll also be surprised to find out which cast member is the biggest hippie and what key piece of show memorabilia burned in Evangeline's house fire.

title: 'Lost' Outside the Box - Interview Part 1

description:
Batman: Arkham City Easter Egg Video in High Definition

===================================

Easter Egg Nr. 10: Lost TV Show

In Batman: Arkham City there are some references to the ABC TV Show "Lost", one of the most popular television series of all time.

Mark Hamill, who voiced the Joker in the game, is a huge fan of the show.

In a small speech during the game, Joker makes a reference to the "Lost" finale by pointing out how it might be disappointing to know all the answers.

"How come it all ended in a church?"

In Arkham City you can also hear thugs saying: "I forget, do they ever explain what the island was?"

This is a clear reference to the mysterious island of the TV show "Lost".

After five seasons of survival, melodrama, time travel, and other wild twists and turns, LOST went into its final season with historical anticipation. The penultimate season ended with one of the craziest cliffhangers in long form storytelling, leaving the final season in uncharted territory. The final season of LOST introduces a major new storytelling element, THE FLASH SIDEWAYS, which was just one of many reasons THE ENDING OF LOST is probably the most divisive ending of all time.

Embark on a captivating journey as we revisit the iconic cast of ‚ÄúLost‚Äù‚Äîfrom their mysterious island adventures to their real-world transformations. Matthew Fox, Evangeline Lilly, Josh Holloway, Naveen Andrews, Jorge Garcia, Terry O‚ÄôQuinn, Yunjin Kim, and Daniel Dae Kim have left an indelible mark on television history.

üï∞Ô∏è Flashback to 2004:

Matthew Fox (Jack Shephard) led the survivors with determination.
Evangeline Lilly (Kate Austen) balanced strength and vulnerability.
Josh Holloway (James ‚ÄúSawyer‚Äù Ford) charmed us with his wit.
Naveen Andrews (Sayid Jarrah) brought depth to his character.
Jorge Garcia (Hugo ‚ÄúHurley‚Äù Reyes) warmed our hearts.
Terry O‚ÄôQuinn (John Locke) intrigued us with his enigma.
Yunjin Kim (Sun-Hwa Kwon) portrayed resilience.
Daniel Dae Kim (Jin-Soo Kwon) navigated love and secrets.
üåü Fast-forward to 2024:

Matthew Fox remains an enigmatic figure, both on and off-screen.
Evangeline Lilly continues to captivate audiences.
Josh Holloway‚Äîstill the charming rogue.
Naveen Andrews‚Äôs journey transcends time.
Jorge Garcia‚Äîa beacon of positivity.
Terry O‚ÄôQuinn‚Äôs intensity endures.
Yunjin Kim‚Äôs grace remains timeless.
Daniel Dae Kim‚Äîa versatile talent.
üì∏ Compare their then-and-now photos as we celebrate the enduring magic of ‚ÄúLost.‚Äù Whether you‚Äôre a devoted fan or a curious newcomer, this video will evoke nostalgia and remind you why this series holds a special place in our hearts.

description:
BrainFeed was an enigmatic and short-lived television program that aired on Channel 69 in Climax, Kentucky. Marketed as a show designed to stimulate viewers' minds, it instead delivered content that was often nonsensical and directionless, leading to widespread confusion and frustration among its audience. The abstract nature of the program prompted numerous viewers to write letters of complaint to the station. After just two episodes, the station manager decided to cancel the show due to the overwhelming negative feedback.√¢‚Ç¨‚Äπ

Years later, fragments of "BrainFeed" resurfaced when a box of VHS tapes was donated to a local Goodwill store. A VHS collector purchased the tapes and, upon discovering the partial recordings of the show, digitized the footage. This unexpected find has since piqued the interest of media enthusiasts and historians, serving as a reminder of the unpredictable nature of television programming and the importance of preserving even the most obscure broadcasts.√¢‚Ç¨‚Äπ

#lost is an American drama television series that aired on ABC from September 22, 2004, to May 23, 2010, over six seasons, comprising a total of 121 episodes. The show contains elements of supernatural and science fiction, and follows the survivors of a commercial jet airliner flying between Sydney and Los Angeles, after the plane crashes on a mysterious island somewhere in the South Pacific Ocean. The story is told in a heavily serialized manner. Episodes typically feature a primary storyline set on the island, augmented by flashback or flashforward sequences which provide additional insight into the involved characters.

Inspired by the 2000 Tom Hanks film Cast Away, Lost was created by Jeffrey Lieber, J. J. Abrams, and Damon Lindelof, who share story writing credits for the pilot episode, which Abrams directed. Throughout the show's run, Lindelof and Carlton Cuse served as showrunners and head writers, working together with many other executive producers and writers. Due to its large ensemble cast and the cost of filming primarily on location in Oahu, Hawaii, the series was one of the most expensive on television, with the pilot alone costing over $14 million. The fictional universe and mythology of Lost were expanded upon by a number of related media, most importantly, a series of short mini-episodes called Missing Pieces, and a 12-minute epilogue titled "The New Man in Charge".

Lost has regularly been ranked by critics as one of the greatest television series of all time. The first season had an estimated average of 16 million viewers per episode on ABC. During its sixth and final season, the show averaged over 11 million U.S. viewers per episode. Lost was the recipient of hundreds of industry award nominations throughout its run and won numerous of these awards, including the Emmy Award for Outstanding Drama Series in 2005, Best American Import at the British Academy Television Awards in 2005, the Golden Globe Award for Best Drama in 2006, and a Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Ensemble in a Drama Series.

description:
Lost captivated audiences from the very beginning with its intricate mythology and mystery box approach to storytelling. The show's sixth and final season, however, proved divisive, as it diverged from fan expectations by prioritizing character resolutions while leaving a lot of questions unanswered.

Initially, "Lost" seemed relatively straight forward as a series, but as things went on, more and more sci-fi weirdness was introduced. Season 6 saw the survivors attempting to prevent the plane crash, aiming to alter the island's fate. Cuz nothing screams easily understandable narrative, quite like timeline manipulation.

Despite audiences expecting concrete resolutions, the final season prioritized metaphysical closure, exploring the characters' emotional journeys. The flash sideways, initially perceived as inconsequential, laid the foundation for the poignant series finale. While opinions on the conclusion are mixed at best, Lost remains a unique and iconic show, that many of us still talk about today, standing as a one-of-a-kind project yet to be matched in the television landscape.

description:
The Brass Tax, lone survivors of a lost psychedelic television show!
This Winchester, Massachusetts area band appeared on the short lived TV show N.H. Bandstand shown on WMUR-9 in Manchester, New Hampshire.
This show featured live local bands and aired film clips of national acts for only a few episodes between 1967-68 before vanishing. This show was a hotspot for local teens as they got chance to be on tv during the dancing segments!
Until now ALL recordings of this show were lost and likely no longer exist as the film was erased to record other shows in an attempt to help the studio save money.
50+ years later a lone cassette emerged from a band member as the result of our extensive search for any remnants. Unheard by the public since the airdate on April 13th, 1968, you can now catch the full show only on Tape Stack!

The Brass Tax - Winchester, Massachusetts.
1. Keep me Hangin' On 0:00
2. A Place In The Sun 7:05
3. Whiskey Man 12:50
4. Hey There, Hi There 16:14
(Written by the band!)
Performed live on the TV show "N.H. Bandstand" hosted by Bill Jones.
April, 13th 1968 - Manchester, New Hampshire - WMUR-TV 9

David Covino - Organ
Steven Ottariano - Rhythm Guitar/Vocals
Joe Bonasera - Drums
Eric O'Brien - Bass
Steve Offenbacher - Lead Guitar

MAN #2
Morning.

JACOB
Mornin'

MAN #2
Mind if I join you?

JACOB
Please ... want some fish?

MAN #2
Thank you. I just ate.

JACOB
I take it you're here because of the ship?

MAN #2
I am ... how did they find the island?

JACOB
You'll have to ask 'em when they get here.

MAN #2
I don't have to ask ... you brought them here. You're trying to proove me wrong, aren't you?

JACOB
You are wrong.

MAN #2
Am I? ... They come; fight; they destroy; they corrupt. It always ends the same.

JACOB
But it only ends once, anything that happens before that ... is just progress.

MAN #2
Do you have any idea how badly I want to kill you?

JACOB
Yes.

MAN #2
One of these days--sooner or later--I'm going to find a loophole, my friend.

JACOB
Well, when you do I'll be right here.

(Beat)

MAN #2
Always nice talking to you, Jacob.

JACOB
Nice talkin' to you, too.

I‚Äôve never seen Lost, but I‚Äôve been getting all sorts of comments lately asking me to react to the medical scenes. Turns out there were a ton of medical moments throughout the series, anchored by Matthew Fox as Dr. Jack Shephard. I reacted to the opening pilot sequence on the beach, Evangeline Lilly as Kate stitching Jack‚Äôs wound, Jack saving Charlie with some chest compressions/chest thumps, Sayid sealing Charlie‚Äôs head wound with fire, Jack performing spinal surgery on Ben‚Äôs tumor, Juliet giving Jack an appendectomy, and the wild ‚ÄúDo Not Harm‚Äù episode where John Locke brings Boone in with a broken leg while Claire is giving birth. So much drama. Any scenes I missed that you want me to react to in a future video? Drop them down below!

Special thanks for helping source these scenes to Brian Tochterman Jr. Erin O‚ÄôConner, Tara Bennett, and the LOST SUPPORT GROUP on Facebook!

description:
Kathy Coleman, Wesley Eure and Phil Paley from Land of the Lost (1974) presented a panel at Amazicon 2019 to talk about the classic show, their experiences and answer fan questions. Plus SINGING!

Kathy Coleman played Holly Marshall on Land of the Lost and is also the author of multiple books and an advocate for mental health organizations.

Wesley Eure played Will Marshall, Holly's older brother in the show and also appeared in CHOMPS and was the writer of Dragon Tales on PBS.

Phillip Paley played Cha-Ka, the Pacuni boy on Land of the Lost. He also appeared on Airwolf and the movie Beach Balls.

These amazing people played characters on one of the best 70's children science fiction shows which still resonates with fans to this day.

To find out more about Amazicon, visit http://amazicon.net/

description:
#lost #shorts #ending

The ending of Lost is famously ambiguous, but it's not a leap to suppose that the 'Sideways' is a product of the electromagnetism/Light, which we already know is also the cause of miracles and the Monster. All of these phenomena fall under the umbrella of the 'magic/mystery box' that feeds flashbacks and inner conflict into the supernatural mysteries. Ben had more of a grasp on it than most, but when he told the truth for once, no one believed him. Remember that Ben half-understood the 'judgement' of the Monster, as it fed on his past guilt, like it does to everyone in the show, Jacob included.

description:
√¢‚Ç¨≈ìYou needed all of them, and they needed you√¢‚Ç¨¬ù

Lost ended on May 23, 2010, and not a day goes by in the last decade where I don√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t think about how much this show means to me. Truly, more than I can even write here, this show has changed my life and will always hold a huge space in my heart.

This is one of my favorite series finales: the first time I watched it every single √¢‚Ç¨≈ìremember√¢‚Ç¨¬ù scene had me sobbing and I watched the last 30 minutes in a haze blurred by my tears. Because Lost was about found family, acceptance, love, and true companionship and the finale highlighted that in a really beautiful way. 

Lost said that your past doesn√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t need to define you, that everyone can change and be better and that there are people in your life who can help you along that journey. It really took all these people who seemingly had nothing in common and said that they can be friends, they can be family. I just love that message so much and I adore these complicated, flawed, human, yet completely lovable characters so much. 

So here√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s a tribute to that, and to the finale that ties that all together. For someone who has defined a life by this show (hello hurleybird), I have struggled immensely in attempting to edit it. For me, capturing all my feelings and emotions and making tributes to Lost seems impossible and anything I make inadequate. But here√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s my attempt, short and sweet, and I hope my fellow Losties enjoy.

SONG: Welcome Home (Reprise) - Radical Face

description:
In 2004, with the rise of new technology and pioneering ideas, Lost, a mysterious new hit show for ABC changed the way we watched television. It altered the landscape in how we, as fans, engaged with our favourite series. This is the story of how Lost changed television fandom forever.

Thank you to:
Jay and Jack Glatfelter - https://www.youtube.com/user/nudiatv
Luke Smith from Hydra Collectibles - https://www.youtube.com/c/HydraCollectables
Gadi Pollock
Additional Footage kindly provided by ToughGamingGuy - https://www.youtube.com/user/ToughGamingGuy

Lost, the show about survivors of a plane crash on a mysterious island, arrived on television in a very traditional sense. But what followed was innovation in the way fans experienced television shows. From the Lost podcasts to the Lost video game (Lost: Via Domus) and Lost ARGs (alternative reality game), Lost pioneered several metaverse strategies that are now commonplace with the latest Netflix and Disney Plus TV shows.

description:
How did a show like Land of the Lost ever get made? The 70s saw some really wild television.  It seemed like TV networks were willing to try anything at least once.  From shows about space age garbage men named Quark, Bionic Couples, or couples who are actually elements like the little known BBC series Sapphire and Steel.  Anything and everything was game for at least one season.
Children√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s programming was even more bizarre, as networks tried to engage kids and teens alike in a time when psychedelic was the norm.  When it came to family and kid√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s TV though, there was one duo who stood proud with a legacy that would dominate the 70s when it came to family programming and put the variety into the word √¢‚Ç¨≈ìvariety show√¢‚Ç¨¬ù.  That duo was Sid and Marty Krofft, and they would be the creators of some of the most iconic TV series to come out of that decade. This would be the era that birthed projects like the Star Wars Holiday Special and several other √¢‚Ç¨≈ìthat was a choice√¢‚Ç¨¬ù holiday themed entertainment.

The Kroffts though, would let their imaginations fly and would go all out with the art and ideas wherever it took take them.  It was within this library of imagination that the Kroffts dived into the land of science fiction and fantasy. The viewers would find themselves lost in that land, along with a dad and his two kids who were just on a routine expedition.

That√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s right kids, grab hold of your life jackets and cuddle a Sleestak, because in this episode of Gone But Not Forgotten we√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢re heading into the Land of The Lost.  But, we won√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t be totally lost as we√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢re going to be guided by not one, not two, but three of the stars of the series as we√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢re joined by Will and Holly. Yes, that√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s right, Wesley Eure, and Kathy Coleman and Cha-Ka himself Phillip Paley are here to give us an insight into the magical land.  So, let√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s dive over that waterfall into The Land of the Lost!

Let us know what you want us to cover on Gone But Not Forgotten in the comments!

description:
There are a handful of shows in the history of television that make an impact so large that it shapes TV for decades. MASH, Cheers, Babylon 5, and Buffy are a few that come to mind. But one the most memorable, was a series about people stranded on a desert island no, not Gilligan's island and no, I am not talking about survivor either. It was of course LOST. This series was not a silly TV show, it was a game-changer. It wasn't focused on storylines but rather a perfect combination of characters and mysteries. Lost is one of those series that still sparks strong emotions from people. Many people love it or hate it. But is the hate for this show misplaced? Is it really that bad or could LOST be one of the greatest TV shows of all time? Let's explore the Island in this episode of Gone but Not Forgotten.

description:
#lost #lostcast #castthenandnow 
I tried finding the best quality (HD) and most recent pictures from all of the actors and actresses in the video. Hopefully you can appreciate the effort.

Lost is an American science fiction drama television series created by Jeffrey Lieber, J.J. Abrams, and Damon Lindelof that aired on ABC from September 22, 2004, to May 23, 2010, over six seasons, comprising a total of 121 episodes. The show contains elements of supernatural fiction, and follows the survivors of a commercial jet airliner flying between Sydney and Los Angeles, after the plane crashes on a mysterious island somewhere in the South Pacific Ocean. Episodes typically feature a primary storyline set on the island, augmented by flashback or flashforward sequences which provide additional insight into the involved characters.

Lindelof and Carlton Cuse serve as showrunners and are executive producers along with Abrams and Bryan Burk. Inspired by the 2000 Tom Hanks film Cast Away, the show is told in a heavily serialized manner. Due to its large ensemble cast and the cost of filming primarily on location in Oahu, Hawaii, the series was one of the most expensive on television, with the pilot alone costing over $14 million. The fictional universe and mythology of Lost were expanded upon by a number of related media, most importantly, a series of short mini-episodes called Missing Pieces, and a 12-minute epilogue titled "The New Man in Charge".

Lost has regularly been ranked by critics as one of the greatest television series of all time. The first season had an estimated average of 16 million viewers per episode on ABC. During its sixth and final season, the show averaged over 11 million U.S. viewers per episode. Lost was the recipient of hundreds of industry award nominations throughout its run and won numerous of these awards, including the Emmy Award for Outstanding Drama Series in 2005, Best American Import at the British Academy Television Awards in 2005, the Golden Globe Award for Best Drama in 2006, and a Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Ensemble in a Drama Series.

LOST 2004-2010

description:
This year is the 20th Anniversary of the TV Show - Lost, which ran from 2004-2010 (6 seasons) on ABC Television in the USA.  Mark Fisher takes you on a tour of the various filming locations for the show on the Island of Oahu in Hawaii.

Lost is Mark's favortive show of all time.  He has watched it from start to finish at least 7 times.   After the show ended, Mark took a trip to Hawaii in September 2013 and got a private tour of the filming locations on the Island of Oahu.  

If you are a fan of the show, or if you have never seen it, you will enjoy this photo trip around the island with Mark.

This is Part 1 of the tour.

Sebbene la serie, andando avanti, spieghi qual √É¬® l√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢origine di questi numeri, in che modo gli sceneggiatori della serie hanno deciso proprio questi numeri?
Uno degli scrittori, David Fury, spieg√É¬≤ che parte dei numeri era stata scelta perch√É¬© gi√É¬† appariva nel corso della serie, come il 4 legato agli anni di Locke in sedia a rotelle e l√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢8 e il 15 che fanno parte del nome del volo che cade sull√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢isola. Nella stessa intervista venne confermato che il 42 √É¬® un omaggio diretto alla Guida Galattica per Autostoppisti ma in seguito gli scrittori affermarono di non voler approfondire ulteriormente l√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢origine dei numeri per non privarli del loro mistero.
Curiosamente, dopo l√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢uscita della serie, nel 2005 la lotteria nazionale estrasse come vincenti tutti i numeri della sequenza, tranne il 42 che usc√É¬¨ invertito come 24.

Von der ersten Folge an machte Lost keine Anstalten, seine Vorliebe f√É¬ºr verwirrende R√É¬§tsel zu verbergen. Und auch das Finale der Serie hat die Zuschauer v√É¬∂llig verwirrt. Wenn ihr also wissen wollt, was wirklich auf der Insel passiert ist, macht euch bereit f√É¬ºr einen tiefen Einblick in das Ende von Lost.

W√É¬§hrend eines Gro√É≈∏teils der Laufzeit von Lost machten sich die Fans Sorgen, dass die Serie mit einer "sie waren die ganze Zeit tot"-Wendung enden w√É¬ºrde. Sch√É¬∂pfer J.J. Abrams und die beiden Showrunner Damon Lindelof und Carlton Cuse dementierten wiederholt Spekulationen, dass die Charaktere bei dem Absturz gestorben seien und die Insel eine Art Fegefeuer sei. Dennoch waren einige Zuschauer der Meinung, dass das Ende des Finales in der Kirche best√É¬§tigte, dass sie die ganze Zeit √É¬ºber gelogen hatten und dass die gesamte Serie im Jenseits stattfand. Diese Interpretation wurde auch durch die Aufnahmen des urspr√É¬ºnglichen Flugzeugabsturzes und der leeren Str√É¬§nde gest√É¬ºtzt, die w√É¬§hrend des Abspannes ausgestrahlt wurden und von denen einige Fans annahmen, dass es keine √É≈ìberlebenden gegeben hatte.

Es stellte sich jedoch heraus, dass die Aufnahmen des Absturzes am Ende nie als Teil des eigentlichen Finales angesehen werden sollten. Stattdessen wurde es, wie ein ABC-Sprecher sp√É¬§ter erkl√É¬§rte, eingef√É¬ºgt, damit sich die Fans, ich zitiere, "entspannen k√É¬∂nnen, bevor sie sich mit den News besch√É¬§ftigen". Der Sender konnte sich nicht vorstellen, dass die Zuschauer dies als Teil der Erz√É¬§hlung der Serie betrachten w√É¬ºrden. Au√É≈∏erdem bem√É¬ºht sich " Das Ende ", ausdr√É¬ºcklich klarzustellen, dass alle Ereignisse, die auf der Insel stattfanden, tats√É¬§chlich real waren.

description:
#LeaveNoQuestionUnanswered #LOSTexplained

The twenty-third chapter in a series of LOST EXPLAINED videos that investigate the mythology and mysteries from the seminal television series LOST. These definitive explanations are based on multiple viewings of the show over the years and careful studying of the details, clues, inconsistencies and contradictions that make up the complex tapestry of what is the greatest television show from the 2000s.

Chapter Twenty-Three lays out the likely history of the Egyptians, whose structures stand the test of time and crop up all over the island within the show. This video will explain the cork, the temple, the summoning chamber(s), the wheel, the statue, the tapestry and hieroglyphs, and the ultimate nature of the island's Egyptian civilization. We will also finally settle the debate on *when* exactly the Egyptians were on the island (was it before or after 'Across the Sea'?), but there are many questions to answer here, such as: why did they build these structures? What was their relationship to Jacob and the Man in Black? Why and how did they die out? All this and much, much more will be revealed in this video.

ABC owns all copyright. The footage and music used in this video are for educational purposes only and fall under fair use.

description: There is an Island on the top left hand side of the map, which has no settlements, so you can not extract here, using the black market. To get here, you either have to fly in a plane or helicopter, or go by boat. As you get closer, your vehicle crashes, and you have to parachute or swim to shore. There is a plane crash on the beach, which is quite similar to the one on the TV Show - Lost. Also is the word 'search' and an arrow. I searched this way and found a hatch, which may or may not be featured on Lost. I don't know because I don't watch it :/ . Aslo on this island is 'The Smoke Monster' I have looked for him, but can't find him anywhere. If you do happen to find him, he looks like an average soldier, but he has no gun, follows you everywhere, is surrounded by smoke, and he cannot die (apparently).

description:
Lost is an American drama television series that originally aired on ABC from September 22, 2004, to May 23, 2010, over six seasons, comprising a total of 121 episodes. The show contains elements of supernatural and science fiction, and follows the survivors of a commercial jet airliner flying between Sydney and Los Angeles, after the plane crashes on a mysterious island somewhere in the South Pacific Ocean. The story is told in a heavily serialized manner. Episodes typically feature a primary storyline set on the island, augmented by flashback or flashforward sequences which provide additional insight into the involved characters.

description:
For some, Lost is seen as one of the greatest shows ever put on television.  A truly ground breaking, survivalist drama that changed the way we think about hour long TV Drama's.   For others, the longer the show went on the more questions they had, with zero answers.   But throughout the entire run of Lost, one episode stands out as truly game changing.  Introducing new ways of story telling, while continuing the concept of JJ Abram's Mystery Box, gave audiences a continued sense of intrigue while expanding the world even more. 

#Lost #PerfectEpisode #Nerdstalgic

Written by Jered Yeaton
Edited by Dan Smiley

Find out what happened to Lost cast after the show finale. In Lost where are they now video we will tell fun facts about Lost TV show behinds the scenes moment and what the cast is up to now after the Lost ending. 

-Henry Ian Cusick aka Desmond Hume - After the show ended, Cusick starred in political thriller Scandal and Marvel√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s Inhumans. Find out about his other roles here! 

-Terry O√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢Quinn aka John Locke - After Lost ended, Terry had one more major change in his life: he divorced with his spouse of 31 years. Watch more about his career and love life in the video. 

-Michael Emerson aka Benjamin Linus - Emerson is 64 but looks super great. Find out what projects he is working on now. 

-Josh Holloway aka James Ford - Josh played in iconic action spy film Mission Impossible - Ghost Protocol. If you miss Sawyer watch our video to find more about his life after the show. 

-Matthew Fox aka Jack Shephard - Matthew is married for 27 years now and is raising two kids. Find out if he is still doing movies. 

-Evangeline Lilly aka Kate Austin - Lilly is doing pretty well balancing her hectic filming schedule and raising up two kids.

Lost is an American drama television series that originally aired on ABC from September 22, 2004, to May 23, 2010, over six seasons, comprising a total of 121 episodes. The show contains elements of supernatural and science fiction, and follows the survivors of a commercial jet airliner flying between Sydney and Los Angeles, after the plane crashes on a mysterious island somewhere in the South Pacific Ocean. The story is told in a heavily serialized manner. Episodes typically feature a primary storyline set on the island, augmented by flashback or flashforward sequences which provide additional insight into the involved characters.

description:
Back in the 60's, The Rolling Stones has appeared in several british and american TV Shows. Most of these appearances was wiped in 1967/68/69. The original broadcast tapes were often re-used by the broadcast companies to record new TV shows, so all the appearances listed in this video is lost forever, including The Rolling Stones' first ever TV appearance. 
I made this video with original photos and lots of research to match properly photo/song/date and make a good video
From a harcore stones fan to another, please enjoy!

Track Listing:

Come On
I Wanna Be Your Man
Not Fade Away
I Just Want To Make Love To You
I'm Alright
Mona (I Need You Baby)
Carol
Good Times, Bad Times
It's All Over Now
OffThe Hook
Down Home Girl
What A Shame
The Last Time
Everybody Needs Somebody To Love
I'm Moving On

TV shows shown in this video:

Thank Your Lucky Stars
Lucky Stars Summer Spin
Lucky Stars Special
Ready Steady Go!
Top Of The Pops
Scene At 6.30
The Clay Cole Saturday Show

Rick, Will, and Holly Marshall find themselves stranded in the Land of the Lost and become fast friends with a young Pakuni called Cha-Ka after rescuing him from a bully named Grumpy.

description:
Hello everyone, Swan Os is a small project, with an operating system very similar in functioning, to the internal computer of the Lost Swan station.
This operating system was created using the ReactOS framework https://reactos.org/
The purpose of this project is to try to make something more similar and surprising than the innumerable programs that simulate the functioning of the swan station computer.
I don't want to take away the credit from these programs, but the idea of an operating system that performs this task seems to me much more scenic and realistic than a program written for windows.

Obviously, as you can see from the video, the huge difference is that the timer is incorporated inside the computer, while as you will remember from the TV series, the timer was physical and hung on the wall.
Other small differences are:
1) The loading screen that anticipates the timer screen has not been shown in the TV series, however i wanted to add it because it is very scenic and pretty.
2) Beep sound, unfortunately due to some software limitations they are not exactly the same and in some computers they cannot be heard (in the video they are reproduced by my pc).

For the rest everything you see and hear is quite faithful to how it happened in the computer of the swan station, the numbers can only be entered when there are less than 4 minutes left, when there are less than 4 minutes left a beep is heard every 2 seconds, when there less than 1 minute a more aggressive beep is heard every 2 seconds, when there are less than 10 seconds left until the sequence is entered a very aggressive beep is heard every second.

When the timer expires the red hieroglyphs will appear on the timer (what you see in the video was the best i could do with a console that only shows CP437 characters) and the wording "System Failure" will repeatedly appear on the screen, from now on if not the lost numbers will be typed in the console within a few seconds, the computer will turn off.

As you can see from the video, the chat with Walt has also been fully implemented which will be activated by pressing the "ESC" button on the keyboard, located in the upper left corner.
In the chat we obviously play Michael, so we should write what Michael really wrote in the TV series to progress with the conversation. The sentences we will write may have different punctuation and/or lowercase/uppercase characters different from the original, it doesn't matter, they will work the same.

HOW TO TRY IT ON A COMPUTER?
Swan OS GitHub page: https://github.com/NikoMac10/Swan-Os
1) Download the zipped iso from the project's GitHub page
2) Extract and burn the iso image with the Rufus program on a usb stick.
3) Check the following rufus settings: partition scheme (MBR), target system (Bios(or UEFI CSM)).
4) Turn on the target computer and enter the bios and set the boot mode to (BIOS/Legacy).
5) If necessary change the boot order of the devices, and put the stick as the first boot device.
6) Enjoy the countdown ;)

If you want you can also test the iso with VMWare or virtualbox, just create the virtual machine and select the iso as boot device.

HOW TO IMPORT THE PROJECT/SOURCE CODE?
1) Do all the listed prerequisites : https://reactos.org/wiki/Building_ReactOS
2) Create a new Cosmos Kernel project on Visual Studio
3) Import the source code of Swan Os (copy and paste)
4) Download and Install VMWare for debugging.

I hope you enjoyed the project and the video, if so leave a like and subscribe.

Credits to the soundtrack music : https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y5PkJ0cJzds&ab_channel=Acorn

description:
For all LOST fans in celebration of the ten year anniversary of the last aired episode from the TV show LOST on May 23, 2010. 



A sample of filming locations visited from 2015 to 2019.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lost_(TV_series)

"Lost is an American drama television series that originally aired on ABC from September 22, 2004, to May 23, 2010, over six seasons, comprising a total of 121 episodes. The show contains elements of supernatural and science fiction, and follows the survivors of a commercial jet airliner flying between Sydney and Los Angeles, after the plane crashes on a mysterious island somewhere in the South Pacific Ocean. The story is told in a heavily serialized manner. Episodes typically feature a primary storyline set on the island, augmented by flashback or flashforward sequences which provide additional insight into the involved characters.Lost was created by Jeffrey Lieber, J. J. Abrams and Damon Lindelof, who share story writing credits for the pilot episode, which Abrams directed. Throughout the show's run, Lindelof and Carlton Cuse served as showrunners and head writers, working together with many other executive producers and writers. Due to its large ensemble cast and the cost of filming primarily on location in Oahu, Hawaii, the series was one of the most expensive on television, with the pilot alone costing over $14 million."


Michael_Giacchino
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Giacchino

"In 2001, J. J. Abrams, producer of the television series Alias, discovered Giacchino through his video game work and asked him to provide the new show's soundtrack. The soundtrack featured a mix of full orchestral pieces frequently intermingled with upbeat electronic music, a departure from much of his previous work. Giacchino would go on to provide the score for J.J. Abrams's 2004 television series Lost."


Michael_Giacchino Tracks used:
From Season 6, Coffin Calamity
From Season 1, Jack FM
From Season 4, Bodies and Bungalows

description:
TV Shows today are not how they used to be. We have some shows that have bigger budgets than blockbuster movies, shows with extremely cinematic storytelling, and with streaming service after streaming service popping up advertising their exclusive shows, it kinda makes you forget that TV shows used to be inferior to movies. Movies used to be an experience and Tv shows were kinda just there to hold you over until the next big movie. Now, it can almost be seen as the opposite. Tv shows now are just movies with a much longer runtime. This seems to be the direction that TV shows are going to be taking from now on, but really none of this was possible without LOST.
